<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=4&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;4</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=6&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;6&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_5.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_5.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>HARD DRIVIN'</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>20 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
This one's an odd one - it was a major Christmas 1989 title with
little in the way of hype and a lot in the way of it feeling more like
a curiosity than a computer game. It charting for a single month as
the Christmas #2 before immediately dropping out never to be seen
again seems to bear out that idea.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Even the appearance of the original arcade only produced a muted
reaction from the press. Instead of raving about the introduction of
filled vector graphics in a driving game there were lots of comments
along the lines of its realism, the fact it has a gearbox, clutch and
even an ignition key to start the engine with. Apparently the arcade
game was created to teach people how to drive, but that just seems to
me to be hyperbole. The fact that the brown cow mooed when you ran
it over appeared to get more coverage than the stunt track.
<TABLE ALIGN="center"><TR><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE  WIDTH=282 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d5_1989_pre3.png" target="1989_pre3.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d5_1989_pre3_small.jpg" WIDTH=282 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>It maybe a simple page design, but that giant arcade map screenshot went a long long way for me. The concept of a stunt track blew my mind.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD VALIGN="top"><TABLE  WIDTH=277 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d5_1989_ad8.png" target="1989_ad8.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d5_1989_ad8_small.jpg" WIDTH=277 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Notice that it's advertised as a "driving simulator"?</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d5_1989_rev4.png" target="1989_rev4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d5_1989_rev4_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=195></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>By the end of 1989, Crash had turned into a pamphlet - Smash reviews were lucky to get a full page, and yet they still persisted in using lots of padding artwork...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/Wqi3O2K-oRU&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/Wqi3O2K-oRU&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Woolworth's Martika Advert (1989)</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">By the end of the '80s, they'd got rid of their song'n'dance adverts, instead going for the more minimalist approach. 'Twas a very sad day when that happened... <b><i>(0:31)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wqi3O2K-oRU" target="Wqi3O2K-oRU">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

And yet it was an important milestone in the evolution of driving
games: a full 3D playing area. OK, so the polygon count was as low as
possible, but the introduction of 3D allowed for the novel "action
replay" feature showing your crash from the point of view of someone
watching in the arena. The one-on-one race at the end of the game
should you complete the Speed Course quick enough also had the nice
touch where it records your own movements and, should you win the
race, your car becomes the car that everyone has to beat the next time
someone reaches the final.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result, there wasn't much hype, really just pure curiosity about
the possibility of a Freescape-style arcade game. It's due to YS's
typical MegaPreview double-page spread that <i>Hard Drivin'</i> is locked
into my memories of Christmas hype as the map of the courses plus the
large screenshots forms a striking image for me.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Crash and YS both gave the game 90%+ ratings, but surprisingly it was
SU who looked beyond the shiny new 3D graphics to see the small and
limited gameplay and marked it down accordingly.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sometimes a novelty really is just a novelty - this is a game every
Speccy player should try, but shouldn't expect to be playing for too
long. But what's Christmas without the odd novelty?!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/steveanderson.png" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;STEVE ANDERSON&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>Steve is a member of that rare breed - the <i>Your Sinclair</i> fan who eventually became one of its writers. What was ZXmas like for you, Steve?</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
I am Steve Anderson. I used to trouble the pages of YS from time to
time. I wrote what is officially the worst covertape game of all time
<a href="http://www.shadowmagic.org.uk/spectrum/covergames.html">according to WoS</a>, something I am obviously very proud of!
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;These days I write (award winning) games for kids and wrangle servers
at work, circuit-bend toys and "be" a "dad" at home, and get together
in a loose association of super-hero scientific minds to debunk
pseudoscience when necessary. (All true!)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?</font></i></b><br>
The overwhelming sense of disappointment, does that count? Otherwise
it's the plastic moustache.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song? <TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/OFCIaMyMORg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/OFCIaMyMORg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Who Framed Roger Rabbit Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">An animated movie before proper 3D graphics really took off - and one of the things which inspired me to take up animation myself. <b><i>(3:14)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OFCIaMyMORg" target="OFCIaMyMORg">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
I'm going to be greedy and take two:
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IippcraBPKA">Just Like Christmas</a> by Low.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BbL9Vsobx8I">We're All Going To Die</a> by Malcolm Middleton.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/B1pZtRjfcgs&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/B1pZtRjfcgs&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>ITV Xmas 1989 Line Up</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A sample of '80s telly on ITV, Xmas Day 1989, including Barrymore and Benny. <b><i>(1:13)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B1pZtRjfcgs" target="B1pZtRjfcgs">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?</font></i></b><br>
About 10 years ago it was just me and my cats for Christmas and Boxing
Day. I borrowed a video projector from work and watched <i>Dawn of the
Dead</i> instead of the Queen, scoffed mince pies a-plenty and played
whatever <i>Tomb Raider</i> was recent at the time into the small hours. It
was great!
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
48K (and I know some other wag will have said this, but - hey - I don't care)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
I favour the Cadbury selection.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
1984: Got my Spectrum. How could that be beaten? My parents split up a
few days later, mind, but for about three days it was awesome. Even
<i>Make-a-Chip</i> rocked.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
<i>Back to Skool</i>. I adored <i>Skool Daze</i> so when I found out there was going
to be a sequel I was cock-a-hoop in the way only a child who has never
been burnt by lazy sequels can be. (Fortunately it was really good,
bugs and all.)
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
